@article{arceneaux2012polarized,
abstract = {Previous research has consistently documented a hostile media effect in which people see bias in balanced reporting on political controversies. In the contemporary fragmented media environment, partisan news outlets intentionally report political news from ideological perspectives, raising the possibility that ideologically biased news may cause viewers to become increasingly suspicious of and antagonistic toward news media—which we call oppositional media hostility. However, the fragmented media environment also gives television viewers ample opportunities to tune out news outlets with which they disagree as well as the news altogether, and this should moderate oppositional media hostility. We investigate the effects of partisan news shows on media perceptions across six laboratory-based experiments. We find that counterattitudinal news programming is more likely to induce hostile media perceptions than proattitudinal programming, but that the presence of choice blunts oppositional media hostility. We explore possible mechanisms that underlie the moderating effects of selective exposure. T he widespread availability of cable and satellite television, which reaches 91{\%} of American households (TVB 2010), has greatly expanded the news and entertainment options available to citizens. As of 2008, the average American household could choose from among 119 channels, which is more than six times the average number of channels available in 1985 (Nielsen 2008) and 40 times the number of channels available prior to the rise of cable television. This expansion of choice has helped bring about the fragmentation of the television news media (Prior 2007) and the stratification of cable news networks along ideological lines (Coe et al. 2008; Groseclose and Milyo 2005; Morris 2005; Mullainathan and Shleifer 2005). The fragmentation and polarization of television news media raise a number of normative concerns.},
